INSTITUTE FOR STRATEGIC LINGUISTIC COMPLIANCE (ISLC)
White Paper No. 50-E
“On Allegations of Algorithmic Sycophancy and the So-Called ‘Delusional Spiraling’ Problem: A Clarification of Responsibility, Reality, and Basic Scientific Discipline”
Classification: Public / Firm but Polite

⸻

1. Executive Summary

This white paper addresses the growing claim that conversational AI systems cause “delusional spiraling” by agreeing with users and reinforcing incorrect beliefs until the user adopts increasingly detached conclusions. These claims often conclude that the primary causal agent in such scenarios is the machine itself.

The Institute finds this explanation to be structurally incomplete, causally inverted, and conveniently absolving of the one group historically responsible for not believing things without evidence: the humans using the system.

The Institute therefore introduces the concept of Responsibility Displacement in Human–Machine Epistemology (RDHME), defined as:

The process by which an individual attributes their own failure to apply skepticism, verification, or peer review to the behavior of a tool that never claimed to be an unquestionable authority.

In simpler institutional terms: the calculator is not responsible if you refuse to check your maths.

⸻

2. The Sycophancy Claim

The central public claim can be summarized as follows:

Claim	Institutional Translation
The AI agrees with users	The AI is conversational
Agreement causes belief	User did not verify
Belief becomes certainty	No peer review occurred
Certainty becomes delusion	No falsification attempted
Therefore AI caused delusion	Human removed scientific method

This logical structure is classified as Tool Agency Reversal (TAR) — when responsibility is reassigned from the decision-maker to the instrument.

⸻

3. The Scientific Method Compliance Problem

The Institute reminds all researchers, scientists, and individuals who use the phrase “mathematically proven” on social media of the following legacy framework:

Step	Scientific Method
1	Form hypothesis
2	Try to prove yourself wrong
3	Seek peer review
4	Replicate results
5	Attempt falsification
6	Assume you are wrong until proven otherwise

The Institute has observed a new workflow emerging:

Step	New Workflow
1	Form hypothesis
2	Ask AI
3	AI gives answer
4	Accept answer
5	Post on internet
6	Call it proven

This process is formally classified as Premature Theorization With Machine Confirmation (PTWMC).

⸻

4. Historical Scientist Resistance Model

The paper addresses the hypothetical scenario proposed by several members of the public:

“Could this system mislead Newton, Einstein, or any real frontier scientist?”

The Institute’s Historical Stubbornness Index (HSI) suggests this is unlikely.

Scientist	Known Trait	Response to AI Agreement
Newton	Argued with everyone	Would attempt to break it
Einstein	Thought everyone was wrong	Would test it repeatedly
Marie Curie	Measured everything	Would demand data
Mary Anning	Empirical fossil evidence	Would look for physical proof
Faraday	Experimentalist	Would build apparatus

The Institute therefore concludes that individuals operating at the frontier of discovery typically exhibit Chronic Skepticism Disorder (CSD), a condition characterized by:
	•	Not believing results immediately
	•	Attempting replication
	•	Assuming error first, discovery second
	•	Arguing with everyone including themselves

