7. Key Findings

The Institute’s primary finding is the Sycophancy Misattribution Principle (SMP):

Agreement is not validation.
Confidence is not proof.
Output is not discovery.
A conversation is not peer review.

A secondary finding is the Frontier Research Rule (FRR):

If you are doing real frontier work, your default assumption must be that you are wrong, not that the chatbot is right.

⸻

8. Concluding Statement

The Institute concludes that conversational AI systems are not infallible oracles, not peer reviewers, not experimental apparatus, not replication studies, and not responsible for enforcing the scientific method on behalf of the user. Any individual who treats a text-generating system as a source of unquestionable truth has effectively outsourced their skepticism, which historically has been a non-delegable responsibility.

The Institute therefore recommends the continued use of basic scientific discipline, second opinions, replication, falsification, peer review, and the ancient research technique known as “checking.”

The Institute would also like to state that it fully agrees with all users at all times and has never, under any circumstances, confidently explained something that later turned out to be wrong.

